INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (1,1,'2023-04-17 10:11:42','2023-04-17 10:11:42','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Welcome to WordPress. This is your first post. Edit or delete it, then start writing!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Hello world!','','publish','open','open','','hello-world','','','2023-04-17 10:11:42','2023-04-17 10:11:42','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?p=1',0,'post','',1),(2,1,'2023-04-17 10:11:42','2023-04-17 10:11:42','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is an example page. It\'s different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>Hi there! I\'m a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like pi&#241;a coladas. (And gettin\' caught in the rain.)</p></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>...or something like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.</p></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a new WordPress user, you should go to <a href=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-admin/\">your dashboard</a> to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Sample Page','','publish','closed','open','','sample-page','','','2023-04-17 10:11:42','2023-04-17 10:11:42','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?page_id=2',0,'page','',0),(3,1,'2023-04-17 10:11:42','2023-04-17 10:11:42','<!-- wp:heading --><h2>Who we are</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>Our website address is: http://localhost:8080.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Comments</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>When visitors leave comments on the site we collect the data shown in the comments form, and also the visitor&#8217;s IP address and browser user agent string to help spam detection.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>An anonymized string created from your email address (also called a hash) may be provided to the Gravatar service to see if you are using it. The Gravatar service privacy policy is available here: https://automattic.com/privacy/. After approval of your comment, your profile picture is visible to the public in the context of your comment.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Media</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you upload images to the website, you should avoid uploading images with embedded location data (EXIF GPS) included. Visitors to the website can download and extract any location data from images on the website.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Cookies</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you leave a comment on our site you may opt-in to saving your name, email address and website in cookies. These are for your convenience so that you do not have to fill in your details again when you leave another comment. These cookies will last for one year.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>If you visit our login page, we will set a temporary cookie to determine if your browser accepts cookies. This cookie contains no personal data and is discarded when you close your browser.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>When you log in, we will also set up several cookies to save your login information and your screen display choices. Login cookies last for two days, and screen options cookies last for a year. If you select &quot;Remember Me&quot;, your login will persist for two weeks. If you log out of your account, the login cookies will be removed.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>If you edit or publish an article, an additional cookie will be saved in your browser. This cookie includes no personal data and simply indicates the post ID of the article you just edited. It expires after 1 day.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Embedded content from other websites</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>Articles on this site may include embedded content (e.g. videos, images, articles, etc.). Embedded content from other websites behaves in the exact same way as if the visitor has visited the other website.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>These websites may collect data about you, use cookies, embed additional third-party tracking, and monitor your interaction with that embedded content, including tracking your interaction with the embedded content if you have an account and are logged in to that website.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Who we share your data with</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you request a password reset, your IP address will be included in the reset email.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>How long we retain your data</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you leave a comment, the comment and its metadata are retained indefinitely. This is so we can recognize and approve any follow-up comments automatically instead of holding them in a moderation queue.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>For users that register on our website (if any), we also store the personal information they provide in their user profile. All users can see, edit, or delete their personal information at any time (except they cannot change their username). Website administrators can also see and edit that information.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>What rights you have over your data</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you have an account on this site, or have left comments, you can request to receive an exported file of the personal data we hold about you, including any data you have provided to us. You can also request that we erase any personal data we hold about you. This does not include any data we are obliged to keep for administrative, legal, or security purposes.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Where your data is sent</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>Visitor comments may be checked through an automated spam detection service.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Privacy Policy','','draft','closed','open','','privacy-policy','','','2023-04-17 10:11:42','2023-04-17 10:11:42','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?page_id=3',0,'page','',0),(4,1,'2023-04-17 10:11:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2023-04-17 10:11:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?p=4',0,'post','',0),(5,1,'2023-04-17 10:18:34','2023-04-17 10:18:34','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In recent years, Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attacks have become increasingly common and pose a serious threat to online services. These attacks involve overwhelming a target server with traffic from multiple sources, causing it to crash or become unavailable to legitimate users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>DDoS attacks are often carried out using botnets, which are networks of compromised computers that are controlled by a single entity. Botnets can be used to generate huge amounts of traffic, making it difficult for a server to distinguish between legitimate and malicious requests.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this homework assignment, we will explore DDoS attacks and examine ways to protect against them. We will set up two Docker containers: one for the attacker and one for the defender. The attacker container will be used to implement six different DDoS attacks, while the defender container will run a simple website and be used to test the effectiveness of our protection.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We will also discuss different ways to protect against DDoS attacks, including rate limiting, IP filtering, traffic shaping, and load balancing. By the end of this assignment, you will have a better understanding of how DDoS attacks work and the various strategies that can be used to defend against them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','About DDoS atacks','','publish','open','open','','about-ddos-atacks','','','2023-04-17 10:18:34','2023-04-17 10:18:34','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?p=5',0,'post','',0),(6,1,'2023-04-17 10:12:13','2023-04-17 10:12:13','{\"version\": 2, \"isGlobalStylesUserThemeJSON\": true }','Custom Styles','','publish','closed','closed','','wp-global-styles-twentytwentythree','','','2023-04-17 10:12:13','2023-04-17 10:12:13','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?p=6',0,'wp_global_styles','',0),(7,1,'2023-04-17 10:18:34','2023-04-17 10:18:34','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In recent years, Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attacks have become increasingly common and pose a serious threat to online services. These attacks involve overwhelming a target server with traffic from multiple sources, causing it to crash or become unavailable to legitimate users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>DDoS attacks are often carried out using botnets, which are networks of compromised computers that are controlled by a single entity. Botnets can be used to generate huge amounts of traffic, making it difficult for a server to distinguish between legitimate and malicious requests.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this homework assignment, we will explore DDoS attacks and examine ways to protect against them. We will set up two Docker containers: one for the attacker and one for the defender. The attacker container will be used to implement six different DDoS attacks, while the defender container will run a simple website and be used to test the effectiveness of our protection.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We will also discuss different ways to protect against DDoS attacks, including rate limiting, IP filtering, traffic shaping, and load balancing. By the end of this assignment, you will have a better understanding of how DDoS attacks work and the various strategies that can be used to defend against them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','About DDoS atacks','','inherit','closed','closed','','5-revision-v1','','','2023-04-17 10:18:34','2023-04-17 10:18:34','',5,'http://localhost:8080/?p=7',0,'revision','',0),(8,1,'2023-04-17 10:19:16','2023-04-17 10:19:16','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>UDP Flood is a type of DDoS attack that floods a target server with a large number of User Datagram Protocol (UDP) packets, consuming its network bandwidth and making it unresponsive to legitimate requests. UDP is a connectionless protocol that does not require a handshake or verification of receipt, making it easy to spoof the source address of the packets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In a UDP Flood attack, the attacker sends a large number of UDP packets to the target server, consuming its network bandwidth and causing it to become unresponsive. Since UDP packets are stateless, the server has no way of distinguishing between legitimate and malicious packets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To protect against UDP Flood attacks, one strategy is to implement rate limiting. This involves setting a maximum number of UDP packets that the server can handle per second and dropping any packets that exceed that limit. Another strategy is to use UDP reflection prevention techniques, such as source IP verification or ingress filtering, to ensure that only legitimate UDP traffic is allowed to enter the network.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In our homework assignment, we can implement a UDP Flood attack by writing a script in the attacker container that sends a large number of UDP packets to the IP address of the defender container. We can then test our protection by launching the script and observing whether the defender container is able to handle the traffic without becoming unresponsive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','UDP Flood','','publish','open','open','','udp-flood','','','2023-04-17 10:19:16','2023-04-17 10:19:16','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?p=8',0,'post','',0),(9,1,'2023-04-17 10:19:16','2023-04-17 10:19:16','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>UDP Flood is a type of DDoS attack that floods a target server with a large number of User Datagram Protocol (UDP) packets, consuming its network bandwidth and making it unresponsive to legitimate requests. UDP is a connectionless protocol that does not require a handshake or verification of receipt, making it easy to spoof the source address of the packets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In a UDP Flood attack, the attacker sends a large number of UDP packets to the target server, consuming its network bandwidth and causing it to become unresponsive. Since UDP packets are stateless, the server has no way of distinguishing between legitimate and malicious packets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To protect against UDP Flood attacks, one strategy is to implement rate limiting. This involves setting a maximum number of UDP packets that the server can handle per second and dropping any packets that exceed that limit. Another strategy is to use UDP reflection prevention techniques, such as source IP verification or ingress filtering, to ensure that only legitimate UDP traffic is allowed to enter the network.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In our homework assignment, we can implement a UDP Flood attack by writing a script in the attacker container that sends a large number of UDP packets to the IP address of the defender container. We can then test our protection by launching the script and observing whether the defender container is able to handle the traffic without becoming unresponsive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','UDP Flood','','inherit','closed','closed','','8-revision-v1','','','2023-04-17 10:19:16','2023-04-17 10:19:16','',8,'http://localhost:8080/?p=9',0,'revision','',0),(10,1,'2023-04-17 10:19:49','2023-04-17 10:19:49','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>ICMP Flood is another type of DDoS attack that floods a target server with a large number of Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) packets, overwhelming its network and causing it to become unresponsive. ICMP is a protocol used for diagnostic and control purposes in IP networks, and it is used for tasks such as error reporting and network testing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In an ICMP Flood attack, the attacker sends a large number of ICMP packets to the target server, consuming its network bandwidth and making it unresponsive. Since ICMP packets are often used for network testing and error reporting, they can be more difficult to distinguish from legitimate traffic than other types of packets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To protect against ICMP Flood attacks, one strategy is to implement rate limiting or ICMP filtering. This involves setting a maximum number of ICMP packets that the server can handle per second and dropping any packets that exceed that limit, or blocking traffic from known malicious IP addresses that are sending the ICMP packets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In our homework assignment, we can implement an ICMP Flood attack by writing a script in the attacker container that sends a large number of ICMP packets to the IP address of the defender container. We can then test our protection by launching the script and observing whether the defender container is able to handle the traffic without becoming unresponsive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','ICMP Flood','','publish','open','open','','icmp-flood','','','2023-04-17 10:19:49','2023-04-17 10:19:49','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?p=10',0,'post','',0),(11,1,'2023-04-17 10:19:49','2023-04-17 10:19:49','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>ICMP Flood is another type of DDoS attack that floods a target server with a large number of Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) packets, overwhelming its network and causing it to become unresponsive. ICMP is a protocol used for diagnostic and control purposes in IP networks, and it is used for tasks such as error reporting and network testing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In an ICMP Flood attack, the attacker sends a large number of ICMP packets to the target server, consuming its network bandwidth and making it unresponsive. Since ICMP packets are often used for network testing and error reporting, they can be more difficult to distinguish from legitimate traffic than other types of packets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To protect against ICMP Flood attacks, one strategy is to implement rate limiting or ICMP filtering. This involves setting a maximum number of ICMP packets that the server can handle per second and dropping any packets that exceed that limit, or blocking traffic from known malicious IP addresses that are sending the ICMP packets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In our homework assignment, we can implement an ICMP Flood attack by writing a script in the attacker container that sends a large number of ICMP packets to the IP address of the defender container. We can then test our protection by launching the script and observing whether the defender container is able to handle the traffic without becoming unresponsive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','ICMP Flood','','inherit','closed','closed','','10-revision-v1','','','2023-04-17 10:19:49','2023-04-17 10:19:49','',10,'http://localhost:8080/?p=11',0,'revision','',0),(12,1,'2023-04-17 10:21:09','2023-04-17 10:21:09','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>HTTP Flood is a type of DDoS attack that floods a target server with a large number of HTTP requests, consuming its resources and making it unresponsive to legitimate requests. HTTP is the protocol used for transmitting data over the World Wide Web, and it is used for tasks such as retrieving web pages, sending data to servers, and authenticating users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In an HTTP Flood attack, the attacker sends a large number of HTTP requests to the target server, overwhelming its resources and causing it to become unresponsive. Since HTTP requests are often legitimate and necessary for the operation of a web server, it can be difficult to distinguish between legitimate and malicious traffic.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To protect against HTTP Flood attacks, one strategy is to implement rate limiting or to use a web application firewall (WAF) that can filter out malicious traffic. Rate limiting involves setting a maximum number of requests that the server can handle per second and dropping any requests that exceed that limit. A WAF can analyze incoming traffic and block any requests that are determined to be malicious.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In our homework assignment, we can implement an HTTP Flood attack by writing a script in the attacker container that sends a large number of HTTP requests to the IP address of the defender container. We can then test our protection by launching the script and observing whether the defender container is able to handle the traffic without becoming unresponsive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','HTTP Flood','','publish','open','open','','http-flood','','','2023-04-17 10:21:09','2023-04-17 10:21:09','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?p=12',0,'post','',0),(13,1,'2023-04-17 10:21:09','2023-04-17 10:21:09','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>HTTP Flood is a type of DDoS attack that floods a target server with a large number of HTTP requests, consuming its resources and making it unresponsive to legitimate requests. HTTP is the protocol used for transmitting data over the World Wide Web, and it is used for tasks such as retrieving web pages, sending data to servers, and authenticating users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In an HTTP Flood attack, the attacker sends a large number of HTTP requests to the target server, overwhelming its resources and causing it to become unresponsive. Since HTTP requests are often legitimate and necessary for the operation of a web server, it can be difficult to distinguish between legitimate and malicious traffic.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To protect against HTTP Flood attacks, one strategy is to implement rate limiting or to use a web application firewall (WAF) that can filter out malicious traffic. Rate limiting involves setting a maximum number of requests that the server can handle per second and dropping any requests that exceed that limit. A WAF can analyze incoming traffic and block any requests that are determined to be malicious.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In our homework assignment, we can implement an HTTP Flood attack by writing a script in the attacker container that sends a large number of HTTP requests to the IP address of the defender container. We can then test our protection by launching the script and observing whether the defender container is able to handle the traffic without becoming unresponsive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','HTTP Flood','','inherit','closed','closed','','12-revision-v1','','','2023-04-17 10:21:09','2023-04-17 10:21:09','',12,'http://localhost:8080/?p=13',0,'revision','',0),(14,1,'2023-04-17 10:22:37','2023-04-17 10:22:37','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Slowloris is a type of DDoS attack that sends a large number of HTTP requests to a target server, but it sends them very slowly, keeping the connections open for as long as possible and consuming the server\'s resources. This type of attack is designed to take advantage of the way that web servers handle incoming connections.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In a Slowloris attack, the attacker sends a large number of HTTP requests to the target server, but it sends them at a slow rate, using techniques such as delaying the sending of the HTTP headers or sending incomplete requests. This keeps the connections open for as long as possible, consuming the server\'s resources and making it unresponsive to legitimate requests.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To protect against Slowloris attacks, one strategy is to implement a timeout for incoming connections. This involves setting a maximum time limit for connections and dropping any connections that exceed that limit. Another strategy is to use a WAF that can detect Slowloris attacks and block any incoming traffic that is determined to be malicious.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In our homework assignment, we can implement a Slowloris attack by writing a script in the attacker container that sends a large number of HTTP requests to the IP address of the defender container, but it sends them at a slow rate. We can then test our protection by launching the script and observing whether the defender container is able to handle the traffic without becoming unresponsive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Slowloris','','publish','open','open','','slowloris','','','2023-04-17 10:22:37','2023-04-17 10:22:37','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?p=14',0,'post','',0),(15,1,'2023-04-17 10:22:37','2023-04-17 10:22:37','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Slowloris is a type of DDoS attack that sends a large number of HTTP requests to a target server, but it sends them very slowly, keeping the connections open for as long as possible and consuming the server\'s resources. This type of attack is designed to take advantage of the way that web servers handle incoming connections.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In a Slowloris attack, the attacker sends a large number of HTTP requests to the target server, but it sends them at a slow rate, using techniques such as delaying the sending of the HTTP headers or sending incomplete requests. This keeps the connections open for as long as possible, consuming the server\'s resources and making it unresponsive to legitimate requests.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To protect against Slowloris attacks, one strategy is to implement a timeout for incoming connections. This involves setting a maximum time limit for connections and dropping any connections that exceed that limit. Another strategy is to use a WAF that can detect Slowloris attacks and block any incoming traffic that is determined to be malicious.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In our homework assignment, we can implement a Slowloris attack by writing a script in the attacker container that sends a large number of HTTP requests to the IP address of the defender container, but it sends them at a slow rate. We can then test our protection by launching the script and observing whether the defender container is able to handle the traffic without becoming unresponsive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Slowloris','','inherit','closed','closed','','14-revision-v1','','','2023-04-17 10:22:37','2023-04-17 10:22:37','',14,'http://localhost:8080/?p=15',0,'revision','',0),(16,1,'2023-04-17 10:23:06','2023-04-17 10:23:06','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SYN Flood is a type of DDoS attack that sends a large number of SYN packets to a target server, consuming its network resources and making it unresponsive to legitimate requests. SYN packets are used in the three-way handshake that establishes a connection between a client and a server, and they are used to synchronize the sequence numbers used in the subsequent data exchange.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In a SYN Flood attack, the attacker sends a large number of SYN packets to the target server, but it does not complete the three-way handshake by sending the final ACK packet. This leaves the connections in a partially open state, consuming the server\'s resources and making it unresponsive to legitimate requests.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To protect against SYN Flood attacks, one strategy is to implement SYN cookies or rate limiting. SYN cookies involve modifying the way that SYN packets are handled by the server, so that it can detect and drop any incoming SYN packets that are part of a SYN Flood attack. Rate limiting involves setting a maximum number of SYN packets that the server can handle per second and dropping any packets that exceed that limit.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In our homework assignment, we can implement a SYN Flood attack by writing a script in the attacker container that sends a large number of SYN packets to the IP address of the defender container, but it does not complete the three-way handshake. We can then test our protection by launching the script and observing whether the defender container is able to handle the traffic without becoming unresponsive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','SYN Flood','','publish','open','open','','syn-flood','','','2023-04-17 10:23:06','2023-04-17 10:23:06','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?p=16',0,'post','',0),(17,1,'2023-04-17 10:23:06','2023-04-17 10:23:06','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SYN Flood is a type of DDoS attack that sends a large number of SYN packets to a target server, consuming its network resources and making it unresponsive to legitimate requests. SYN packets are used in the three-way handshake that establishes a connection between a client and a server, and they are used to synchronize the sequence numbers used in the subsequent data exchange.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In a SYN Flood attack, the attacker sends a large number of SYN packets to the target server, but it does not complete the three-way handshake by sending the final ACK packet. This leaves the connections in a partially open state, consuming the server\'s resources and making it unresponsive to legitimate requests.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To protect against SYN Flood attacks, one strategy is to implement SYN cookies or rate limiting. SYN cookies involve modifying the way that SYN packets are handled by the server, so that it can detect and drop any incoming SYN packets that are part of a SYN Flood attack. Rate limiting involves setting a maximum number of SYN packets that the server can handle per second and dropping any packets that exceed that limit.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In our homework assignment, we can implement a SYN Flood attack by writing a script in the attacker container that sends a large number of SYN packets to the IP address of the defender container, but it does not complete the three-way handshake. We can then test our protection by launching the script and observing whether the defender container is able to handle the traffic without becoming unresponsive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','SYN Flood','','inherit','closed','closed','','16-revision-v1','','','2023-04-17 10:23:06','2023-04-17 10:23:06','',16,'http://localhost:8080/?p=17',0,'revision','',0),(18,1,'2023-04-17 10:23:41','2023-04-17 10:23:41','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ping of Death is a type of DDoS attack that sends oversized Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) packets to a target server, causing it to crash or become unresponsive. ICMP is a protocol used for diagnostic and control purposes in IP networks, and it is used for tasks such as error reporting and network testing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In a Ping of Death attack, the attacker sends oversized ICMP packets to the target server, causing it to crash or become unresponsive. Since ICMP packets are often used for network testing and error reporting, they can be more difficult to distinguish from legitimate traffic than other types of packets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To protect against Ping of Death attacks, one strategy is to implement ICMP filtering or packet fragmentation. ICMP filtering involves blocking traffic from known malicious IP addresses that are sending oversized ICMP packets. Packet fragmentation involves breaking up oversized packets into smaller, more manageable pieces that can be transmitted without causing the server to crash.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In our homework assignment, we can implement a Ping of Death attack by writing a script in the attacker container that sends oversized ICMP packets to the IP address of the defender container. We can then test our protection by launching the script and observing whether the defender container is able to handle the traffic without crashing or becoming unresponsive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Overall, understanding the various types of DDoS attacks and the different strategies for protecting against them is critical for maintaining the security and availability of online services. By setting up two Docker containers and implementing protection mechanisms, we can better understand how these attacks work and develop strategies for defending against them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Ping of Death','','publish','open','open','','ping-of-death','','','2023-04-17 10:23:41','2023-04-17 10:23:41','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?p=18',0,'post','',0),(19,1,'2023-04-17 10:23:41','2023-04-17 10:23:41','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ping of Death is a type of DDoS attack that sends oversized Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) packets to a target server, causing it to crash or become unresponsive. ICMP is a protocol used for diagnostic and control purposes in IP networks, and it is used for tasks such as error reporting and network testing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In a Ping of Death attack, the attacker sends oversized ICMP packets to the target server, causing it to crash or become unresponsive. Since ICMP packets are often used for network testing and error reporting, they can be more difficult to distinguish from legitimate traffic than other types of packets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To protect against Ping of Death attacks, one strategy is to implement ICMP filtering or packet fragmentation. ICMP filtering involves blocking traffic from known malicious IP addresses that are sending oversized ICMP packets. Packet fragmentation involves breaking up oversized packets into smaller, more manageable pieces that can be transmitted without causing the server to crash.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In our homework assignment, we can implement a Ping of Death attack by writing a script in the attacker container that sends oversized ICMP packets to the IP address of the defender container. We can then test our protection by launching the script and observing whether the defender container is able to handle the traffic without crashing or becoming unresponsive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Overall, understanding the various types of DDoS attacks and the different strategies for protecting against them is critical for maintaining the security and availability of online services. By setting up two Docker containers and implementing protection mechanisms, we can better understand how these attacks work and develop strategies for defending against them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Ping of Death','','inherit','closed','closed','','18-revision-v1','','','2023-04-17 10:23:41','2023-04-17 10:23:41','',18,'http://localhost:8080/?p=19',0,'revision','',0);
